'''Frank Klepacki''' (born [[May 25]], [[1974]]) is an [[Wikipedia:United States|American]] musician, video game music composer and sound director best known for his work on the [[Wikipedia:Command & Conquer series|''Command & Conquer'' series]]. Having learned to play drums as a child, he joined [[Wikipedia:Westwood Studios|Westwood Studios]] as a composer when he was only 17 years old. He scored several games there, including the [[Wikipedia:Lands of Lore|''Lands of Lore'' series]], the [[Wikipedia:Dune II|''Dune'' games]], the [[Wikipedia:The Legend of Kyrandia|''The Legend of Kyrandia'' series]], [[Wikipedia:Blade Runner (video game)|''Blade Runner'']], and the ''Command & Conquer'' series. His work in [[Wikipedia:Command & Conquer: Red Alert|''Command & Conquer: Red Alert'']] won two awards.

Klepacki is currently the audio director of [[Petroglyph]] games, where he scored ''[[Star Wars: Empire at War]]'' and [[Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption|its expansion]]. Frank Klepacki was contacted to score [[Wikipedia:Command & Conquer 3: Tiberium Wars|''Command & Conquer 3: Tiberium Wars'']], but was too busy with Petroglyph to take the project, and declined to mention the offer.

==Biography==
{{Quote|Greetings, this is Urai Fen. A recent addition to the Zann Consortium is Frank Klepacki. He's recorded so much f''[bleeped]'' V.O. that he's about to lose his mind.|Frank Klepacki, in a recorded outtake|audio=FoCBlooperKlepackiOuttake.flac|<ref name="Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption">''[[Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption]]''</ref>}}
His first task was scoring ''[[Star Wars: Empire at War]]'', Petroglyph's launch title; he also helped select voice actors.<ref name="askpetroglyph1">{{WebCite|url=http://petroglyphgames.com/forums/index.php?hl=klepacki&showtopic=1012|text=Some questions for everyone at Petroglyph|work=[http://www.petroglyphgames.com/forums Petrogylph Forums]|archivedate=20160310025119}}</ref> A die-hard fan of the Star Wars franchise, Klepacki enjoyed complementing [[John Williams]]'s style as he worked with sound effects used in the feature films.<ref name="music4gamesinterview">{{WebCite|url=http://www.music4games.net/Features Display.aspx?id=6|text=Interview with Star Wars: Empire At War Audio Director and composer Frank Klepacki|author=Music4Games staff|date=2006-01-22|work=[http://www.music4games.net Music4Games]|nobackup=1}}</ref> He worked closely with programmers to ensure perfect aural functionality. Though most the game's score is John Williams's work, Klepacki estimates that he contributed 20% original material. Apart from the main theme, he aimed to minimize his editing in order to retain the classic ''Star Wars'' sound.<ref name="music4gamesinterview" /> He chiefly composed for new areas of the ''Star Wars'' universe only found in ''Empire at War''. He calls his work on the game "the peak of my career,"<ref name="petroglyphpodcast">{{WebCite|url=http://www.petroglyphgames.com/news/index.php?id=60&year=2006|text=Frank Klepacki Podcast|work=[http://www.petroglyphgames.com Petroglyph Games]|archivedate=20061021194725}}</ref> and felt he had spent his entire life grooming his abilities for that soundtrack.<ref name="gwjinterview">{{WebCite|url=http://www.gamerswithjobs.com/taxonomy/term/318|text=Gamers With Jobs Radio: Interview with Frank Klepacki|date=21-03-06|work=[http://www.gamerswithjobs.com Gamers with Jobs]|archivedate=20051026042700}}</ref> As a perk of composing, he visited [[Skywalker Ranch]] and [[Industrial Light & Magic]], and took pride in having his name associated with an official ''Star Wars'' product.<ref name="twincities">{{WebCite|url=http://www.twincities.com/2007/05/22/fans-share-their-star-wars-memories|text=Fans share their Star Wars memories|author=Pioneer Press|date=2007-05-23|work=[http://www.twincities.com Twin Cities]|archivedate=20160306074543}}</ref><ref name="readerswrite">{{WebCite|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/movies/2007/05/13/The-Readers-Write-Star-Wars-memories/stories/200705130153|text=The Readers Write: 'Star Wars' memories|date=2007-05-25|work=[http://www.post-gazette.com Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]|archivedate=20160108012131}}</ref>

[[File:Klepackipetroglyphstudios.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Frank Klepacki at his Petroglyph office]]
For the ''Forces of Corruption'' expansion pack, he took greater creative liberty with the ''Star Wars'' feel by writing an original theme for the new criminal faction.<ref name="petroglyphpodcast" /> In attempting to compose this piece, he wrote several preliminary hooks that were later integrated into the game's battle themes.<ref name="gamespotdiary5">{{GameSpot|url=articles/star-wars-empire-at-war-forces-of-corruption-designer-diary-5-the-sounds-of-corruption/1100-6159916|text=Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption Designer Diary #5 - The Sounds of Corruption|author=Frank Klepacki|date=2006-10-17}}</ref> He composed six pieces for the expansion total, including the finale theme. In line with the criminal theme of the game, Klepacki borrowed motifs and recreated the mood from scenes involving [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba the Hutt]] in [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Return of the Jedi'']].<ref name="music4gamesfoc">{{WebCite|url=http://www.music4games.net/Features_Display.aspx?id=119|text=Star Wars: Empire at War - Forces of Corruption Interview with Audio Director and Composer Frank Klepacki|date=2006-12-05|work=[http://www.music4games.net Music4Games]|archivedate=20070829145624}}</ref> His score for the expansion pack was accepted upon first submission to [[LucasArts]].<ref name="music4gamesfoc" /> As Petrogylph's audio director, he also selected sound effects—a tricky process due to the issue of making the criminal faction's sounds a "little different, without straying too much from the original signature sounds."<ref name="gamespotdiary5" /> Klepacki worked with LucasArts to select voice actors, and contributed his own talents to the role of [[IG-88A/Legends|IG-88]] and other minor characters.<ref name="gamespotdiary5" /> A blooper reel of his voice acting was released on Petroglyph's forums after the one-thousandth member registered.<ref name="focblooper">{{WebCite|url=http://www.petroglyphgames.com/forums/index.php?showtopic=1511|text=Frank's FOC Bloopers!|work=[http://www.peroglyphgames.com Petroglyph Games]|archivedate=20181205003517}}</ref>

